{
  "chapters": [
    {
      "description": "Start with a royal letter, a map, and a traveler’s account from 1500 to see how Portuguese newcomers described the land and the people they met. You practice reading early sources like a historian and ask what these documents show, hide, and distort.",
      "title": "Reading the First Records of Portuguese Arrival"
    },
    {
      "description": "This chapter follows the many Indigenous peoples already living in the territory before and during early colonization. It covers social life, trade, warfare, language, land use, and the ways Indigenous groups resisted, negotiated, and survived.",
      "title": "Indigenous Worlds in the Land That Became Brazil"
    },
    {
      "description": "Sugar mills, forced labor, ports, and Atlantic trade turned colonization into a business. This chapter shows how plantations worked and how the colony was tied to Portugal, Africa, and global markets.",
      "title": "Sugar, Slavery, and the Colonial Economy"
    },
    {
      "description": "Millions of Africans were brought to Brazil through violence and coercion. You trace the slave trade, daily life under slavery, family and religion, rebellion, quilombos, and the deep marks slavery left on Brazilian society.",
      "title": "Atlantic Slavery and Afro-Brazilian Life"
    },
    {
      "description": "Colonial Brazil was not ruled only from Lisbon. This chapter looks at missionaries, settlers, local elites, militias, and church power, showing how authority worked on the ground and why it was often contested.",
      "title": "Power, Faith, and Rule in Colonial Brazil"
    },
    {
      "description": "Gold and diamonds changed the colony’s center of gravity in the 1700s. You follow mining towns, tax systems, migration, social change, and the tensions that grew as wealth and control collided.",
      "title": "Mining, Towns, and the Interior"
    },
    {
      "description": "Ideas of revolt did not begin in the 1800s. This chapter covers conspiracies, uprisings, and reform movements in the late colonial period, including Minas Gerais and Bahia, placing them in Atlantic context.",
      "title": "Conspiracies and Colonial Revolts"
    },
    {
      "description": "The transfer of the Portuguese court to Rio reshaped the colony in dramatic ways. You see how war in Europe changed Brazil’s status, economy, institutions, and path toward separation from Portugal.",
      "title": "The Royal Court in Rio de Janeiro"
    },
    {
      "description": "Independence was a political break, but not a social reset. This chapter traces the crisis with Portugal, the role of Dom Pedro, regional struggles, and the limits of independence for enslaved people, Indigenous communities, and the poor.",
      "title": "Independence and the Birth of the Empire"
    },
    {
      "description": "Brazil’s first decades as an empire were unstable and contested. You follow the constitution, the emperor’s powers, regional rebellions, and the hard work of holding together a huge new state.",
      "title": "Building the Imperial State"
    },
    {
      "description": "Coffee wealth transformed labor, land, and political power in the 1800s. This chapter shows how expansion into the southeast connected slavery, immigration, railroads, and export growth.",
      "title": "Coffee and the Nineteenth-Century Economy"
    },
    {
      "description": "Brazil ended the Atlantic slave trade long before it ended slavery itself. You trace abolitionism, resistance by enslaved people, legal steps toward freedom, and the political crisis that led to 1888.",
      "title": "The Long Road to Abolition"
    },
