      "description": "The monarchy fell, but the new republic was not fully democratic. This chapter covers military rule, federalism, coronelismo, regional oligarchies, and the everyday limits of citizenship in the First Republic.",
      "title": "The First Republic"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cities grew, factories spread, and new social groups entered public life. You examine immigration, labor movements, anarchism, early industry, sanitation, and the changing shape of urban Brazil.",
      "title": "Immigration, Work, and Urban Life"
    },
    {
      "description": "The crisis of the old republic opened the way for Getúlio Vargas. This chapter follows the 1930 Revolution, centralization, labor law, nationalism, propaganda, and the Estado Novo dictatorship.",
      "title": "Vargas and the Remaking of the State"
    },
    {
      "description": "After World War II, Brazil saw both democratic hope and deep instability. This chapter covers party politics, development projects, culture, rural conflict, and the tensions that led to the 1964 coup.",
      "title": "Democracy and Crisis after 1945"
    },
    {
      "description": "The military regime used censorship, repression, and institutional control while also pushing economic growth. You trace dictatorship, resistance, the so-called economic miracle, inequality, and everyday life under authoritarian rule.",
      "title": "Dictatorship, Repression, and the Military State"
    },
    {
      "description": "Brazil’s return to civilian rule brought mass mobilization and a new constitutional order. This chapter follows Diretas Já, the 1988 Constitution, new social movements, and the rebuilding of democratic institutions.",
      "title": "Redemocratization and the 1988 Constitution"
